UserAccessor.createUser(String username) has been deprecated, but there is not embedded crowd equivalent, since a credential is required in CrowdService.addUser(User, String credential) that may not be empty or blank. This is a problem for both SSO authenticators (like Confluence Shibboleth Authenticator) that do not know the password and for plugins like Confluence Space User Management that allow creation of users that don't yet exist to add them to groups in the case where an SSO authenticator that does not provide a password will be used, in which case it is perfectly acceptable to have a user in Confluence/Crowd that has no password. Storing a fake password is risky- it should allow a user to have a null password which indicates that user cannot login via credential (since there is none) but could login via authenticator, such as an SSO authenticator. Without this change, things will break and people won't be able to upgrade Confluence if and when that UserAccessor method becomes unsupported in the future.

